In [[quantum field theory in curved spacetime]], there is a whole class of quantum states over a background [[de Sitter space]] which are invariant under all the [[isometries]]: the alpha-vacua. Among them there is a particular one whose associated Green functions verify a condition (Hadamard condition) consisting to behave on the light-cone as in flat space. This state is usually called the '''Bunch–Davies vacuum''' or '''Euclidean vacuum''',<ref> {{cite journal | last1 = Bunch | first1 = Timothy Stephen | last2 = Davies | first2 = Paul | authorlink2 = Paul Davies | year = 1978 | title = Quantum Field Theory In De Sitter Space: Renormalization By Point Splitting | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society of London | volume = 360 | series = A | pages = 117 | doi = 10.1098/rspa.1978.0060 |bibcode = 1978RSPSA.360..117B }} </ref> actually was first obtained by N.A. Chernikov and E. A. Tagirov, in 1968<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Chernikov | first1 = N.A. | last2 = Tagirov | first2 = E. A. | year = 1968 | title = Quantum theory of scalar field in de Sitter space-time | journal = Annales de l'Institut Henri Poincaré | volume = IX, 2 | series = A | pages = 109 }} </ref> and later by C. Schomblond and P. Spindel, in 1976, in the framework of a general discussion about invariant Green functions on de Sitter space.<ref> {{cite journal | last1 = Schomblond | first1 = Christiane | last2 = Spindel | first2 = Philippe | year = 1976 | title = Conditions d'unicit e pour le propagateur Delta 1(x; y) du champ scalaire dans l'univers de de Sitter | journal = Annales de l'Institut Henri Poincaré | volume = XXV, 1 | series = A | pages = 67 }} </ref> The Bunch–Davies vacuum can also be described as being generated by an infinite time trace from the condition that the scale of quantum fluctuations is much smaller than the [[Hubble expansion|Hubble scale]].<ref name=jhep>{{cite journal|last=Danielsson|first=Ulf H|author2=Olsson, Martin E|title=On thermalization in de Sitter space|journal=Journal of High Energy Physics|date=15 March 2004|volume=2004|issue=03|pages=036–036|doi=10.1088/1126-6708/2004/03/036|arxiv=hep-th/0309163|bibcode = 2004JHEP...03..036D }}</ref> The state possesses no quanta at the asymptotic past infinity.<ref name=picon>{{cite journal|last=Armendariz-Picon|first=C|title=Why should primordial perturbations be in a vacuum state?|journal=Journal of Cosmology and Astroparticle Physics|date=26 February 2007|volume=2007|issue=02|pages=031–031|doi=10.1088/1475-7516/2007/02/031|arxiv=astro-ph/0612288|bibcode = 2007JCAP...02..031A }}</ref>
The Bunch-Davies state is the zero-particle state as seen by a [[geodesic]] observer, that is, an observer who is in free fall in the expanding state.<ref name=green(2006)>{{cite journal|last=Greene|first=Brian R |author2=Parikh, Maulik K |author3=van der Schaar, Jan Pieter |title=Universal correction to the inflationary vacuum|journal=Journal of High Energy Physics|date=28 April 2006|volume=2006|issue=04|pages=057–057|doi=10.1088/1126-6708/2006/04/057|arxiv=hep-th/0512243|bibcode = 2006JHEP...04..057G }}</ref> The state explains the origin of [[Primordial fluctuations|cosmological perturbation]] fluctuations in inflationary models.
== See also ==
* [[Quantum field theory in curved spacetime]] * [[Unruh effect]] * [[Hawking radiation]] * [[Inflation (cosmology)]]
