{{About|the crater on Mars|the crater on the Moon|Janssen (lunar crater)}} {{Infobox Mars crater | name = Janssen Crater | image = JanssenMartianCrater.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = Location of Janssen Crater | region = [[Arabia quadrangle]] | coordinates = {{coord|2.7|N|38.5|E|globe:mars_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | discoverer = | diameter = 158 km | eponym = [[Pierre Janssen]] }} [[File:Wikijanssen.jpg|thumb|Eastern edge of Janssen Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]]).]] [[File:Wikijanssenstreaks.jpg|thumb|Layers and [[dark slope streaks]] in northeastern edge of Janssen Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter). Note: this is an enlargement of the previous image of Janssen Crater.]] '''Janssen Crater''' is an impact crater in the [[Arabia quadrangle]] on Mars at 2.7° N and 322.5° W. and is 158.0&nbsp;km in diameter, it is also in the north of [[Terra Sabaea]]. Its name was approved in 1973, and it was named after [[Pierre Janssen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature {{!}} Janssen|url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/2801|website=usgs.gov|publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]]|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref> Some close up images of the crater reveal layers in a floor deposit. A picture below show these layers, as well as [[dark slope streaks]]. The darker the streak, the younger it is. The layers on the floor of Janssen may have been formed on the bottom of lakes.<ref>Cabrol, N. and E. Grin. 2001. The Evolution of Lacustrine Environments on Mars: Is Mars Only Hydrologically Dormant? Icarus: 149, 291-328.</ref><ref>Fassett, C. and J. Head. 2008. Open-basin lakes on Mars: Distribution and implications for Noachian surface and subsurface hydrology. Icarus: 198, 37-56.</ref><ref>Fassett, C. and J. Head. 2008. Open-basin lakes on Mars: Implications of valley network lakes for the nature of Noachian hydrology.</ref>
Nearby prominent and named craters include [[Teisserenc de Bort (crater)|Teisserenc de Bort]] crater in the east, Tuscaloosa to the west and the large [[Tikhonravov (crater)|Tikhonravov]] for the north. Some tens of kilometers to the west is a valley known as [[Naktong Vallis]].
